<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06048121 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06048121 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; TAX; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  If you have a Touch-Tone telephone, you can get recorded answers to the mostcommon state income tax questions through an automated toll-free state taxinformation service.;     That phone system, nicknamed FAST (Fast Answersabout State Taxes), also can be used to ask about the status of your refundafter you have filed. The automated tax question service is (800) 338-0505,and it works this way:  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HOW TO CONTACT STATE TAX BOARD  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Step-By-Step Tax Guide;  See also related story on page 1E-8E in this sectionwith headline;  The 540: A Step-by-Step Guide  </MEMO><TEXT>     A computer answers your call and instructs you to push the asterisk on yourTouch-Tone phone and then dial a three-digit code for your specific question.If you want to ask how to file for an extension, for example, you dial 201,and if you want to ask about an IRA deduction, you dial 211.;     Thetraditional tax assistance number, in which you talk with a real person from 7a.m. to 10 p.m. Monday through Friday, is (800) 852-5711. The number for thehearing impaired is (800) 822-6268. Tax assistance at these numbers will beavailable on two Saturdays, April 6 and 13.;     Family members of reservistsor military personnel serving in the Persian Gulf should call (800) 852-5711for more information.;     The tax board's San Jose office is at 96 N. ThirdSt., on the fourth floor, and is open from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday throughFriday. Workers will accept payments and hand out forms, but they don'tprovide advice.;     Tax forms are also available at most libraries and atmany post offices.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Stories by Broderick Perkins, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910217  </PUBDATE> <DA